document.title: Alabama Course of Study  DIGITAL LITERACY AND  COMPUTER SCIENCE

42AD002CA3994F7491D7BEBF48ED1294.description:
Use an iterative design process, including learning from mistakes, to gain a better
understanding of a problem domain.

1E5B8160F82945999AF4F16DDA45289D.description:
Identify a problem that cannot be solved by either humans or machines alone and discuss a
solution for it by decomposing the task into sub-problems suited for a human or machine to
accomplish.
Examples: Forecasting weather, piloting airplanes.

FC70A25752DA4277A0963D687B546743.description:
Systematically design and develop programs for broad audiences by incorporating feedback
from users.
Examples: Games, utilities, mobile applications.

D902ED5D48894EAF850454A1AF369885.description: Explore situations where a flawed model provided an incorrect answer.

63C56A4F3EFE42A7A3F4BC5FCBC545E3.description:
Form a model of a hypothesis, testing the hypothesis by the collection and analysis of data
generated by simulations.
Examples: Science lab, robotics lab, manufacturing, space exploration.

A7B9645EC7F847D9B69A6E951CD21127.description: Create and utilize models and simulations to help formulate, test, and refine a hypothesis.

7DDFAE5D15C849698626C0B47D4D12ED.description: Evaluate the ability of models and simulations to test and support the refinement of hypotheses.

08C6920A88004E4AA86EC0313DBBCE3F.description:
Explain the tradeoffs when selecting and implementing cybersecurity recommendations.
Examples: Two-factor authentication, password requirements, geolocation requirements.

BF10D93CFAE24EC8B6AA1803048FAE3B.description:
Appraise the role of artificial intelligence in guiding software and physical systems.
Examples: predictive modeling, self-driving cars.

AB5DA434135242A59A73561241D0EDD5.description: Categorize the roles of operating system software.

BC25DF46C34A48FC8B702E04670453E2.description:
Understand the need for networking protocols and examples of common protocols.
Examples: HTTP, SMTP, and FTP

F508AA6D157C43AD9D35C7F8C2FF39EA.description:
Explain the purpose of Internet Protocol addresses and how domain names are resolved to
IP addresses through a Domain Name System server.

C8782AEF622A4FA6A7A76BC520A79A4C.description:
Evaluate the scalability and reliability of networks by describing the relationship between
routers, switches, servers, topology, packets, or addressing, as well as the issues that impact
network functionality.
Examples: Bandwidth, load, delay.

66BAB174178146D19F5015FFB77E7D68.description:
Use data analysis tools and techniques to identify patterns in data representing complex
systems.

8004D83F7FEE42F4B0ECD93B20292CCA.description:
Create interactive data visualizations using software tools to help others understand real-world
phenomena.

E4648D48C422470D9E535FEC20F1F6FB.description:
Evaluate the tradeoffs involved in choosing methods for the organization of data elements and
the location of data storage, including the advantages and disadvantages of networked
computing.
Examples: Client server, peer-to-peer, cloud computing.

C7D900F0A44B49F0B0E4D0E4F6B66EAB.description:
Summarize the role of compression and encryption in modifying the structure of digital
artifacts and the varieties of information carried in the metadata of these artifacts.

7EC80CED03524281B202807974B449CE.description:
Develop a model that reflects the methods, procedures and concepts used by computing
devices in translating digital bits as real-world phenomena, such as print characters, sound,
images, and video.

E4554B530F9D49BF922B1D2A35290AB9.description:
Apply tools and methods for collaboration on a project to increase connectivity among people
in different cultures and career fields.
Examples: Collaborative documents, webinars, teleconferencing, and virtual fieldtrips

D71E5FFA2E42415493D851B37F16C44B.description:
Use collaborative technologies to work with others including peers, experts, or community
members to examine local, national, and global issues and problems from multiple viewpoints.

8893777A26EF4FCAA165DD01AACD9829.description: Utilize a variety of digital tools to create digital artifacts across content areas.

2C3E6A787B124FA486A30C6119E3C085.description:
Apply version control capabilities within a digital tool to understand the importance of
managing historical changes across suggestions made by a collaborative team.

97B9691756A0485988AFC69B55F1237C.description:
Compare and contrast Internet publishing platforms, including suitability for media types,
target audience, and feedback mechanism.

CD83E9A8061C42E8A4B926FA88691DF4.description:
Debate the positive and negative effects of computing innovations in personal, ethical, social,
economic, and cultural spheres.
Examples: Artificial Intelligence/machine learning, mobile applications, automation of
traditional occupational skills.

F01F1499B9A340E6820891EB71BE8691.description:
Research the impact of computing technology on possible career pathways.
Examples: Government, business, medicine, entertainment, education, transportation.

21DE57B13E974A29A0DED1940DCDFCA3.description:
Explain how technology facilitates the disruption of traditional institutions and services.
Examples: Digital currencies, ridesharing, autonomous vehicles, retail, Internet of Things.

5FAF70E10D5B43C9A9C146A1B9E51D9F.description:
Evaluate strategies to manage digital identity and reputation with awareness of the permanent
impact of actions in a digital world.

5D5A2F3075144B80BC350F67BBA66032.description: Prove that digital identity is a reflection of persistent, publicly available artifacts.

2231B4D851784DC3B8919A4A6276E6A6.description:
Explain the beneficial and harmful effects that intellectual property laws can have on
innovation.

3415D5F1B54D4DF3AF1AD8AD0BFC1F76.description:
Discuss the ethical ramifications of malicious hacking and its impact on society.
Examples: Dissemination of privileged information, ransomware.

14AD909C773846E18CA4B80E1982DA45.description:
Identify laws regarding the use of technology and their consequences and implications.
Examples: Unmanned vehicles, net neutrality/common carriers, hacking, intellectual property,
piracy, plagiarism.

27F4B59A41714A40954D0D85CAD49EF3.description: Explain the necessity for the school’s Acceptable Use Policy.

11EDCDA144274F479200F91D23B02F71.description: Compare ways to protect devices, software, and data.

B8E9EFB4916A418E9FC7B01F39C62F27.description:
Compare various security measures of a computer system.
Examples: Usability, security, portability, and scalability.

5F2B3B0B0DB548329CAC3391B767B7F2.description: Describe how sensitive data can be affected by malware and other attacks.

84C15BC2B19D4D4B83A87936A951AC83.description:
Explain strategies to lessen the impact of negative digital behaviors and assess when to
apply them.

A193DC64F8D242EEA15882E63B612FD3.description:
Identify physical, legal, and ethical consequences of inappropriate digital behaviors.
Examples: Cyberbullying/harassment, inappropriate sexual communications.

512FC6A408A64ED690B4CB6C90073335.description:
Explain the relationship between online privacy and personal security.
Examples: Convenience and accessibility, data mining, digital marketing, online wallets,
theft of personal information.

66EA701EB2F144ACA57459D1A012C632.description:
Understand the ramifications of end-user license agreements and terms of service
associated with granting rights to personal data and media to other entities.

90889B6363EE4E2EB8AFBC619CC7A13E.description: Understand how to apply techniques to mitigate effects of user tracking methods.

E139F02510A64626BB9FF4226E08E5D1.description:
Recognize user tracking methods and hazards.
Examples: Cookies, WiFi packet sniffing.

0B6DEF1FC1FD4C79B6939C9797A53E69.description:
Model and demonstrate behaviors that are safe, legal, and ethical while living, learning, and
working in an interconnected digital world.

6AE0A5497B044837B8E0FC1459F3C508.description:
Resolve or debug errors encountered during testing using iterative design process.
Examples: Test for infinite loops, check for bad input, check edge-cases.

9117EC4D2CC94244AE617178EE3089CD.description:
Collaborate in a code review process to identify correctness, efficiency, scalability and
readability of program code.

CCB06B729BB646CCA10D2E9F2C4529B0.description:
Develop and use a series of test cases to verify that a program performs according to its
design specifications

EB7F38B5021341C5AA07266C81DBEBDC.description: Demonstrate the ability to verify the correctness of a program.

433587516E6045F882F426B8EE489084.description:
Demonstrate code reuse by creating programming solutions using libraries and Application
Programming Interfaces.

A1C806D62A2A4196AED28473531307DA.description:
Compare and contrast fundamental data structures and their uses.
Examples: Strings, lists, arrays, stacks, queues.

2A1D72BB449E4798960D9D3F6991AE7D.description:
Decompose problems into smaller components through systematic analysis, using constructs
such as procedures, modules, and/or objects, with parameters, and which return a result.

75124E3D5349423780B05ACEEC82BF31.description:
Design and iteratively develop computational artifacts for practical intent, personal expression,
or to address a societal issue by using current events.

AF90F874C2F84649A1C318B5B979376D.description:
Use and adapt classic algorithms to solve computational problems.
Examples: Sorting, searching, shortest path, and data compression.

FEDAD23D7F06451DB31F6F595E65250F.description:
Explain how more than one algorithm may solve the same problem and yet be
characterized with different priorities.
Examples: All self-driving cars have a common goal of taking a passenger to a
designation but may have different priorities such as safety, speed, or conservation; web
search engines have their own algorithms for search with their own priorities.

7B91DF3F74C744CE9851784AC87A94DB.description:
Evaluate and select algorithms based on performance, reusability, and ease of
implementation.

CF8B66C2064F4817ACDCD4D8ABAAE4EB.description:
Distinguish when a problem solution requires decisions to be made among alternatives,
such as selection constructs, or when a solution needs to be iteratively processed to arrive
at a result, such as iterative “loop” constructs or recursion.

37CA7A5F06814470B9C2514D401737A4.description:
Compare and contrast the difference between specific control structures such as sequential
statements, conditional, iteration, and explain the benefits and drawbacks of choices made.
Examples: Tradeoffs involving implementation, readability, and program performance.

15E6DDE71E6140799A15985D32683FAB.description:
Explain that some algorithms do not lead to exact solutions in a reasonable amount of time
and thus approximations are acceptable.

BE18443C0CC04D2295757DADBF537519.description:
Differentiate between a generalized expression of an algorithm in pseudocode and its concrete
implementation in a programming language.

B4A20912FD084956B02543ECAD96E563.description:
Explain how computing systems are often integrated with other systems and embedded in ways
that may not be apparent to the user.
Examples: Millions of lines of code control the subsystems within an automobile (e.g., antilock
braking systems, lane detection, and self-parking).

AB851B8DD7444D19BEBA13BA026323F9.description:
Decompose problems into component parts, extract key information, and develop descriptive
models to understand the levels of abstractions in complex systems.
